<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec_warmups" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Warmup Problems</title>
  <worksheet>
    <title>Warmup Problems</title>
    <introduction>
    <p>The questions on this handout will help give an overview of
    where linear algebra begins.</p>
    </introduction>
    <page>

    <activity workspace="4cm">
    <task xml:id="task_warmups_simult">
    <p>Solve:
    <md>
      <mrow>3x_1-2x_2\amp= 6</mrow>
      <mrow>-x_1+x_2\amp= 1</mrow>
    </md>
    </p>
    </task>

    <task>
      <statement>
	<p>Draw a graph of the solution set of the equation: <m>3x_1-2x_2=6</m>.
	</p>
      </statement>
      <hint>
	<p>If a solution has <m>x_1=a</m>, what is <m>x_2</m> or viceversa?
	</p>
      </hint>
    </task>

    <task>
      <p>Draw a graph of the solution set of the equation:
      <m>-x_1+x_2=1</m>.</p>
    </task>

    <task>
      <p>Graph the solution sets from the two previous steps
  together. How does your answer to <xref
  ref="task_warmups_simult">part</xref> compare to your graph?
      </p>
    </task>
</activity>
    </page>
    <page>
<activity workspace="5cm">
  <statement>
    <p>Solve:
  <md>
    <mrow>2x_1-2x_2\amp=6</mrow>
    <mrow>-x_1+x_2\amp=1 </mrow>
  </md>
    </p>
  </statement>
</activity>

<activity workspace="5cm">
  <statement>
  <p>Solve:
  <md>
    <mrow>2x_1-2x_2\amp=-2</mrow>
    <mrow>-x_1+x_2\amp=1</mrow>
  </md>
  </p>
  </statement>
</activity>

<investigation workspace="3cm">
  <statement>
  <p>Wait&#8230;what just happened? Explain the results of the previous
  two activities. What do the graphs of the corresponding solution sets
  look like in relation to the graphs of the equations?
  </p>
  </statement>
</investigation>

<investigation workspace="3cm">
  <statement>
  <p>What are the possible intersections of two lines? Clearly state
  your conjecture.
  </p>
  </statement>
</investigation>

<p>Throughout this course we will be doing many of the same things you
did in the previous questions, but we will do them in a more general
setting that will allow us to solve <em>many</em> new and old
problems.</p>
    </page>
  </worksheet>
</section>

